<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,623,151,177]" box="[151,623,151,177]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,623,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,623,151,177]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[207,449,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intersecta">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,449,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Paradelia intersecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,226,412]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
The following four species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Meigen" authorityName="Meigen" box="[484,846,226,252]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intersecta">
<emphasis box="[484,725,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Paradelia intersecta</emphasis>
(Meigen)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[858,966,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. a rc t i c a</emphasis>
(Ringdahl), 
<taxonomicName authority="Schnabl" authorityName="Schnabl" box="[1121,1436,226,252]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignotaeformis">
<emphasis box="[1121,1314,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. ignotaeformis</emphasis>
(Schnabl)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[200,297,266,291]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. m a n n i</emphasis>
sp. nov., are small and dark-coloured and have no setulae on the 
<emphasis box="[1061,1076,266,291]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">d</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1132,1145,266,291]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">v</emphasis>
surfaces of wing vein C. Two characters support the monophyly of this species group: (
<number box="[883,895,306,332]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1.0">1</number>
) male sternite V (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[1166,1307,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURES 69 – 74" captionStartId="39.[151,269,1599,1623]" captionTargetBox="[199,1405,215,1559]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[161,1426,194,1575]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 69 – 74. Paradelia intersecta, male. 69, 70. Sternite V, lateral and ventral views. 71, 72. Hypopygium, caudal and lateral views. 73. Pre- and postgonites, lateral view. 74. Phallus, lateral view. Same scale for 69, 70 and 71 – 74 respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178608/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Figs. 
<number box="[1232,1307,306,332]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="69.7">69, 70</number>
</figureCitation>
) with nonsetose, angular lamella of each lobe continued far backward as a thin, blade-like, outer lamella in shape of a ploughshare; and (
<number box="[368,384,386,412]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2.0">2</number>
) male tergite VI very short, fused together with synsclerite VII–VIII.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
